title: What would happen if half the nitrogen in our atmosphere was turned into fluorine? - Quora

response.answer_text: What would happen if half the nitrogen in our atmosphere was turned into fluorine? The short version is: everybody dies. The atmosphere is now 39% fluorine. Fluorine is a nasty bastard- it will react with anything. But more importantly for our purposes, when it comes into contact with water it forms hydrofluoric acid, which is horribly corrosive. It’s also a contact poison. It’s highly toxic and can be absorbed through the skin. The burns don’t show up straight away, and you can’t feel it because the first thing it does is kill all your nerve endings. And by the time the burns show up it’s already too late, because when the stuff reaches your bones it reacts with the calcium in them to form calcium difluoride- it literally robs your bones of calcium. And now the entire ocean is made of this stuff. Lakes. Rivers. All deadly corrosive poison. And the inside of your throat and lungs are moist. So when you take a breath, the fluoride reacts and forms this horrible stuff inside you. Which makes you very, very dead. You and everyone else.

A2A: Everyone Dies™. Gruesomely, quickly, and with great vigor. A lot of things on the surface of the planet change. Fluorine will react with just about anything. Fluorine don’t care. Fluorine don’t give a shit. That much fluorine in the air? The world’s oceans turn into dilute hydrofluoric acid, and man, things get interesting though nobody will be alive to see it. (I mean, for God’s sake, sand dissolves in HF!) The world’s landscape is altered in fun and exciting ways. The weather changes. The geography changes. Millions of voices cry out in terror and are suddenly silenced. It would be carnage on a scale undreamed of in all the end-times fantasies by all the world’s religions. (Did I mention HF dissolves sand?)

response.answer_text: Dilute aqueous HF is a weak acid, but at concentrations greater than 20%, severe and potentially lethal burns can occur. Hydrofluoric acid behaves as a strong acid at concentrations > 50%. Burns covering even a small surface area can be fatal. Unlike strong acids, HF is highly penetrative due to primarily being in the non-dissociated state, causing deep tissue destruction via liquefactive necrosis and allowing for easy entry into the systemic circulation. Once within the tissues, the fluoride ion complexes with calcium and magnesium, causing their depletion. Hyperkalemia results from increased cellular permeability and inhibition of the Na+/K+ pump. Neuron depolarization and severe pain result from these electrolyte abnormalities. Fluoride also causes myocardial irritability, predisposing to dysrhythmia. Don't Get Burned by Hydrofluoric Acid Toxicity Warning: 3 2 1 This is a hand burnt by HF acid.  It can react with H2O, producing HF acid, Oxygen and Ozone. So once the F gas is present in the atmosphere, the reaction will take place quickly, turning water vapour and water into HF acid.
